{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509192"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:14:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:14:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11401"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11401"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.14,0.38,0.18,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4037"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109867"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4037"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11401"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92236"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"4891"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6563"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4627"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4628"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5962"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7799"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12790"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13435"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14764"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28416"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41188"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42587"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109867","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109867"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 81-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department one-hour after a brief episode of collapse at home, which occurred when she stood up quickly from her chair. She then quickly regained consciousness whilst lying on the floor. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She denies any chest pain, palpitations, shortness of breath or headache preceding the fall. She has not had any previous similar episodes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. A right-sided carotid bruit is heard. Neurological and cardiovascular examinations are otherwise unremarkable. Among the initial investigations that are undertaken, a carotid duplex ultrasound reveals a 74% stenosis of the right internal carotid. MRI Brain was normal, excluding a cerebrovascular accident (CVA).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Medical therapy","Carotid artery stenting","Carotid endarterectomy within 14 days","Elective carotid endarterectomy","Non-urgent vascular surgical review"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECurrent guidelines for managing carotid artery disease differentiate between symptomatic and asymptomatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely experienced orthostatic hypotension, causing transient loss of consciousness. The 74% right internal carotid stenosis is an incidental finding and unlikely to be the cause in this case.  Symptomatic carotid disease describes events in the previous six months, typically presents with focal neurological deficits (e.g., transient ischaemic attack or stroke, dysphasia or mono-ocular vision loss), not syncope. Isolated vertigo or syncope without focal deficits are classified as asymptomatic, even with carotid stenosis. As such, the patient\u0027s carotid stenosis is classified as asymptomatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment for symptomatic versus asymptomatic carotid stenosis varies as the plaques for symptomatic carotid stenosis are considered \u0027unstable\u0027 and at higher risk of complications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedical therapy\u003C/strong\u003E for cardiovascular risk reduction is the first-line approach for managing asymptomatic carotid artery stenosis. Studies indicate that with intensive medical management, the annual risk of stroke in asymptomatic carotid stenosis is less than 1%. Treatment typically includes potent lipid-lowering agents, antiplatelet therapy, and antihypertensive medications, alongside lifestyle modifications such as smoking cessation, dietary changes, and regular exercise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn asymptomatic carotid stenosis, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarotid endarterectomy\u003C/strong\u003E can reduce the stroke rate but studies show that the benefit is small, and the procedure itself has a significant stroke risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn symptomatic carotid artery disease, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarotid endarterectomy within 14 days\u003C/strong\u003E would be the most appropriate management option. For symptomatic carotid stenosis of 50-99%, management typically involves carotid endarterectomy (CEA) or carotid angioplasty and stenting, ideally within 14 days of symptom onset. However, the benefit of intervention is more modest for 50-69% stenosis compared to higher degrees of narrowing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid artery stenting\u003C/strong\u003E has no role in the management of asymptomatic carotid artery stenosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Enon-urgent vascular surgical review\u003C/strong\u003E may be appropriate for carotid artery stenosis \u0026gt;80% in younger patients with minimal comorbidities, as they have the greatest potential to benefit from stroke risk reduction over their lifetime. The decision should be based on a careful assessment of the cumulative stroke reduction benefit of surgery, weighed against the risks of the procedure and the effectiveness of intensive medical management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, carotid endarterectomy, is reserved for symptomatic cases, defined by ipsilateral amaurosis fugax, contralateral limb weakness, or speech disturbances, and should ideally occur within 14 days. Asymptomatic cases are typically managed with medical therapy, but a vascular surgical review may be considered in younger patients with \u0026gt;80% stenosis if their lifetime stroke risk is high.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intensive medical therapy is the first line approach to the management of asymptomatic carotid artery disease.","The benefit of surgery for symptomatic carotid artery stenosis is greatest within 2 weeks of a TIA or mild stroke."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Managing asymptomatic carotid stenosis. Therapeutic Guidelines. November, 2017. Accessed October 2, 2022. https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.eu1.proxy.openathens.net/viewTopic?etgAccess=true\u0026guidelinePage=Neurology\u0026topicfile=managing-asymptomatic-carotid-stenosis\u0026guidelinename=Neurology\u0026sectionId=toc_d1e467#toc_d1e467","Mullen M, Jim J. Management of asymptomatic extracranial carotid atherosclerotic disease. UpToDate. August 11, 2022. Accessed October 2, 2022. https://www.uptodate.com/contents/management-of-asymptomatic-extracranial-carotid-atherosclerotic-disease?search=carotid%20artery%20stenosis\u0026topicRef=1118\u0026source=related_link#H1491439557Management of asymptomatic extracranial carotid atherosclerotic disease","Arasu R, Arasu A, Muller J. Carotid artery stenosis: An approach to its diagnosis and management. Australian Journal of General Practice. Updated November, 2021. Accessed October 2, 2022. https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2021/november/carotid-artery-stenosisCarotid artery stenosis: An approach to its diagnosis and management","Naylor, A. R., et al. \u0022Editor\u0027s choice\u2013management of atherosclerotic carotid and vertebral artery disease: 2017 clinical practice guidelines of the European Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS).\u0022 European Journal of Vascular and Endovascular Surgery 55.1 (2018): 3-81."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92236"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11401"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92236"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-27T12:18:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T12:18:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4037"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109867"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"